# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: barebox
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:barebox/barebox] The Barebox project began in July 2007 as u-boot-v2, as it was derived from Das U-Boot, but with heavier borrowings from Linux like similar utilities and with a more Linux-like coding style.
[src:barebox/booting] This may be done by hardware or firmware in the CPU, or by a separate processor in the computer system.
[src:barebox/booting] On some systems, a power-on reset (POR) does not initiate booting, and the operator must initiate booting after POR completes.
[src:barebox/booting] IBM uses the term **Initial Program Load** (**IPL**) on some product lines.
[src:barebox/booting] Restarting a computer is also called *rebooting*, which can be "hard", e.g., after electrical power to the CPU is switched from off to on, or "soft", where the power is not cut.
[src:barebox/booting] On some systems, a soft boot may optionally clear RAM to zero.
[src:barebox/booting] Both hard and soft booting can be initiated by hardware, such as a button press, or by a software command.
[src:barebox/booting] Booting is complete when the operative runtime system, typically the operating system and some applications, is attained.
[src:barebox/booting] The process of returning a computer from a state of sleep (suspension) does not involve booting; however, restoring it from a state of hibernation does.
[src:barebox/booting] Minimally, some embedded systems do not require a noticeable boot sequence to begin functioning, and when turned on, may simply run operational programs that are stored in read-only memory (ROM).
[src:barebox/booting] All computing systems are state machines, and a reboot may be the only method to return to a designated zero-state from an unintended, locked state.
[src:barebox/booting] In addition to loading an operating system or stand-alone utility, the boot process can also load a storage dump program for diagnosing problems in an operating system.
[src:barebox/booting] The earliest known recorded use of "boot" as the shortened form for "bootstrap" is 1975.
[src:barebox/booting] There are many different methods available to load a short initial program into a computer.
[src:barebox/booting] These methods range from simple, physical input to removable media that can hold more complex programs.
[src:barebox/booting] Early computers in the 1940s and 1950s were one-of-a-kind engineering efforts that could take weeks to program, and program loading was one of many problems that had to be solved.
[src:barebox/booting] An early computer, ENIAC, had no program stored in memory but was set up for each problem by a configuration of interconnecting cables.
[src:barebox/booting] Bootstrapping did not apply to ENIAC, whose hardware configuration was ready for solving problems as soon as power was applied.
[src:barebox/booting] The EDSAC system, the second stored-program computer to be built, used stepping switches to transfer a fixed program into memory when its start button was pressed.
[src:barebox/booting] The program stored on this device, which David Wheeler completed in late 1948, loaded further instructions from punched tape and then executed them.
[src:barebox/booting] The first programmable computers for commercial sale, such as the UNIVAC I and the IBM 701 included features to make their operation simpler.
[src:barebox/booting] They typically included instructions that performed a complete input or output operation.
[src:barebox/booting] The same hardware logic could be used to load the contents of a punch card (the most typical ones) or other input media, such as a magnetic drum or magnetic tape, that contained a bootstrap program by pressing a single button.
[src:barebox/booting] This booting concept was called a variety of names for IBM computers of the 1950s and early 1960s, but IBM used the term "Initial Program Load" with the IBM 7030 Stretch and later used it for their mainframe lines, starting with the System/360 in 1964.
[src:barebox/booting] The IBM 701 computer (1952–1956) had a "Load" button that initiated reading of the first 36-bit word into main memory from a punched card in a card reader, a magnetic tape in a tape drive, or a magnetic drum unit, depending on the position of the Load Selector switch.
[src:barebox/booting] The left 18-bit half-word was then executed as an instruction, which usually read additional words into memory.
[src:barebox/booting] The loaded boot program was then executed, which, in turn, loaded a larger program from that medium into memory without further help from the human operator.
[src:barebox/booting] The IBM 704, IBM 7090, and IBM 7094 had similar mechanisms, but with different load buttons for different devices.
[src:barebox/booting] The term "boot" has been used in this sense since at least 1958.
[src:barebox/booting] Other IBM computers of that era had similar features.
[src:barebox/booting] For example, the IBM 1401 system (1959) used a card reader to load a program from a punched card.
[src:barebox/booting] The 80 characters stored in the punched card were read into memory locations 001 to 080, then the computer would branch to memory location 001 to read its first stored instruction.
[src:barebox/booting] This instruction was always the same: move the information in these first 80 memory locations to an assembly area where the information in punched cards 2, 3, 4, and so on, could be combined to form the stored program.
[src:barebox/booting] Once this information was moved to the assembly area, the machine would branch to an instruction in location 080 (read a card) and the next card would be read and its information processed.
[src:barebox/booting] Another example was the IBM 650 (1953), a decimal machine, which had a group of ten 10-position switches on its operator panel that were addressable as a memory word (address 8000) and could be executed as an instruction.
[src:barebox/booting] Thus, setting the switches to 7004000400 and pressing the appropriate button would read the first card in the card reader into memory (op code 70), starting at address 400 and then jump to 400 to begin executing the program on that card.
[src:barebox/booting] IBM's competitors also offered single-button program load.
[src:barebox/booting] A noteworthy variation of this is found on the Burroughs B1700, where there is neither a boot ROM nor a hardwired IPL operation.
[src:barebox/booting] Instead, after the system is reset, it reads and executes microinstructions sequentially from a cassette tape drive mounted on the front panel; this sets up a boot loader in RAM, which is then executed.
[src:barebox/booting] However, since this makes few assumptions about the system it can equally well be used to load diagnostic (Maintenance Test Routine) tapes which display an intelligible code on the front panel even in cases of gross CPU failure.
[src:barebox/booting] In the IBM System/360 and its successors, including the current z/Architecture machines, the boot process is known as *Initial Program Load* (IPL).
[src:barebox/booting] IBM coined this term for the 7030 (Stretch), revived it for the design of the System/360, and continues to use it in those environments today.
[src:barebox/booting] In the System/360 processors, an IPL is initiated by the computer operator by selecting the three hexadecimal digit device address (CUU; C=I/O Channel address, UU=Control unit and Device address) followed by pressing the *LOAD* button.
[src:barebox/booting] On the high end System/360 models, most System/370 and some later systems, the functions of the switches and the LOAD button are simulated using selectable areas on the screen of a graphics console, often an IBM 2250-like device or an IBM 3270-like device.
[src:barebox/booting] For example, on the System/370 Model 158, the keyboard sequence 0-7-X (zero, seven and X, in that order) results in an IPL from the device address that was keyed into the input area.
[src:barebox/booting] The Amdahl 470V/6 and related CPUs supported four hexadecimal digits on those CPUs that had the optional second channel unit installed, for a total of 32 channels.
[src:barebox/booting] Later, IBM would also support more than 16 channels.
[src:barebox/booting] The IPL function in the System/360 and its successors prior to IBM Z, and its compatibles, such as Amdahl's, reads 24 bytes from an operator-specified device into main storage starting at real address zero.
[src:barebox/booting] The second and third groups of eight bytes are treated as Channel Command Words (CCWs) to continue loading the startup program (the first CCW is always simulated by the CPU and consists of a Read IPL command, 02h, with command chaining and suppress incorrect length indication being enforced).
[src:barebox/booting] When the I/O channel commands are complete, the first group of eight bytes is then loaded into the processor's Program Status Word (PSW) and the startup program begins execution at the location designated by that PSW.
[src:barebox/booting] IBM introduced some evolutionary changes in the IPL process, changing some details for System/370 Extended Architecture (S/370-XA) and later, and adding a new type of IPL for z/Architecture.
[src:barebox/booting] Minicomputers, starting with the Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) PDP-5 and PDP-8 (1965) simplified design by using the CPU to assist input and output operations.
[src:barebox/booting] This saved cost but made booting more complicated than pressing a single button.
[src:barebox/booting] Minicomputers typically had some way to *toggle in* short programs by manipulating an array of switches on the front panel.
[src:barebox/booting] Since the early minicomputers used magnetic-core memory, which did not lose its information when power was off, these bootstrap loaders would remain in place unless they were erased.
[src:barebox/booting] Erasure sometimes happened accidentally when a program bug caused a loop that overwrote all of memory.
[src:barebox/booting] Other minicomputers with such simple form of booting include Hewlett-Packard's HP 2100 series (mid-1960s), the original Data General Nova (1969), and DEC's PDP-4 (1962) and PDP-11 (1970).
[src:barebox/booting] As the I/O operations needed to cause a read operation on a minicomputer I/O device were typically different for different device controllers, different bootstrap programs were needed for different devices.
[src:barebox/booting] DEC later added, in 1971, an optional diode matrix read-only memory for the PDP-11 that stored a bootstrap program of up to 32 words (64 bytes).
[src:barebox/booting] It consisted of a printed circuit card, the M792, that plugged into the Unibus and held a 32 by 16 array of semiconductor diodes.
[src:barebox/booting] With all 512 diodes in place, the memory contained all "one" bits; the card was programmed by cutting off each diode whose bit was to be "zero".
[src:barebox/booting] DEC also sold versions of the card, the BM792-Yx series, pre-programmed for many standard input devices by simply omitting the unneeded diodes.
[src:barebox/booting] Following the older approach, the earlier PDP-1 has a hardware loader, such that an operator needs only push the *load* switch to instruct the paper tape reader to load a program directly into core memory.
[src:barebox/booting] The PDP-7, PDP-9, and PDP-15 successors to the PDP-4 have an added Read-In button to read a program in from paper tape and jump to it.
[src:barebox/booting] The Data General Supernova used front panel switches to cause the computer to automatically load instructions into memory from a device specified by the front panel's data switches, and then jump to loaded code.
[src:barebox/booting] In a minicomputer with a paper tape reader, the first program to run in the boot process, the boot loader, would read into core memory either the second-stage boot loader (often called a *Binary Loader*) that could read paper tape with checksum or the operating system from an outside storage medium.
[src:barebox/booting] A related example is based on a loader for a Nicolet Instrument Corporation minicomputer of the 1970s, using the paper tape reader-punch unit on a Teletype Model 33 ASR teleprinter.
[src:barebox/booting] The bytes of its second-stage loader are read from paper tape in reverse order.
[src:barebox/booting] The length of the second stage loader is such that the final byte overwrites location 7.
[src:barebox/booting] After the instruction in location 6 executes, location 7 starts the second stage loader executing.
[src:barebox/booting] The second stage loader then waits for the much longer tape containing the operating system to be placed in the tape reader.
[src:barebox/booting] The difference between the boot loader and second stage loader is the addition of checking code to trap paper tape read errors, a frequent occurrence with relatively low-cost, "part-time-duty" hardware, such as the Teletype Model 33 ASR.
[src:barebox/booting] The earliest microcomputers, such as the Altair 8800 (released first in 1975) and an even earlier, similar machine (based on the Intel 8008 CPU) had no bootstrapping hardware as such.
[src:barebox/booting] When powered up, the CPU would see memory that would contain random data.
[src:barebox/booting] The front panels of these machines carried toggle switches for entering addresses and data, one switch per bit of the computer memory word and address bus.
[src:barebox/booting] Simple additions to the hardware permitted one memory location at a time to be loaded from those switches to store bootstrap code.
[src:barebox/booting] Meanwhile, the CPU was kept from attempting to execute memory content.
[src:barebox/booting] Once correctly loaded, the CPU was enabled to execute the bootstrapping code.
[src:barebox/booting] This process, similar to that used for several earlier minicomputers, was tedious and had to be error-free.
[src:barebox/booting] The introduction of integrated circuit read-only memory (ROM), with its many variants, including mask-programmed ROMs, programmable ROMs (PROM), erasable programmable ROMs (EPROM), and flash memory, reduced the physical size and cost of ROM.
[src:barebox/booting] This allowed firmware boot programs to be included as part of the computer.
[src:barebox/booting] The Data General Nova 1200 (1970) and Nova 800 (1971) had a program load switch that, in combination with options that provided two ROM chips, loaded a program into main memory from those ROM chips and jumped to it.
[src:barebox/booting] Digital Equipment Corporation introduced the integrated-circuit-ROM-based BM873 (1974), M9301 (1977), M9312 (1978), REV11-A and REV11-C, MRV11-C, and MRV11-D ROM memories, all usable as bootstrap ROMs.
[src:barebox/booting] An Italian telephone switching computer, called "Gruppi Speciali", patented in 1975 by Alberto Ciaramella, a researcher at CSELT, included an (external) ROM.
[src:barebox/booting] Gruppi Speciali was, starting from 1975, a fully single-button machine booting into the operating system from a ROM memory composed of semiconductors, not ferrite cores.
[src:barebox/booting] Although the ROM device was not natively embedded in the computer of Gruppi Speciali, due to the design of the machine, it also allowed the single-button ROM booting in machines not designed for that (therefore, this "bootstrap device" was architecture-independent), e.g., the PDP-11.
[src:barebox/booting] Storing the state of the machine after the switch-off was also in place, which was another critical feature in the telephone switching contest.
[src:barebox/booting] Some minicomputers and superminicomputers include a separate console processor that bootstraps the main processor.
[src:barebox/booting] The PDP-11/44 had an Intel 8085 as a console processor; the VAX-11/780, the first member of Digital's VAX line of 32-bit superminicomputers, had an LSI-11-based console processor, and the VAX-11/730 had an 8085-based console processor.
[src:barebox/booting] These console processors could boot the main processor from various storage devices.
[src:barebox/booting] Some other superminicomputers, such as the VAX-11/750, implement console functions, including the first stage of booting, in CPU microcode.
[src:barebox/booting] A system built using that microprocessor will have the permanent ROM occupying these special locations so that the system always begins operating without operator assistance.
[src:barebox/booting] For example, Intel x86 processors always start by running the instructions beginning at F000:FFF0, while for the MOS 6502 processor, initialization begins by reading a two-byte vector address at $FFFD (MS byte) and $FFFC (LS byte) and jumping to that location to run the bootstrap code.
[src:barebox/booting] Apple Computer's first computer, the Apple 1, introduced in 1976, featured PROM chips that eliminated the need for a front panel for the boot process (as was the case with the Altair 8800) in a commercial computer.
[src:barebox/booting] Due to the expense of read-only memory at the time, the Apple II booted its disk operating systems using a series of very small incremental steps, each passing control onward to the next phase of the gradually more complex boot process.
[src:barebox/booting] Because so little of the disk operating system relied on ROM, the hardware was also extremely flexible and supported a wide range of customized disk copy protection mechanisms.
[src:barebox/booting] Some operating systems, most notably pre-1995 Macintosh systems from Apple, are so closely interwoven with their hardware that it is impossible to natively boot an operating system other than the standard one.
[src:barebox/booting] This is the opposite extreme of the scenario using switches mentioned above; it is highly inflexible but relatively error-proof and foolproof as long as all hardware is working normally.
[src:barebox/booting] A common solution in such situations is to design a boot loader that works as a program belonging to the standard OS that hijacks the system and loads the alternative OS.
[src:barebox/booting] This technique was used by Apple for its A/UX Unix implementation and copied by various freeware operating systems and BeOS Personal Edition 5.
[src:barebox/booting] Some machines, like the Atari ST microcomputer, were "instant-on", with the operating system executing from a ROM.
[src:barebox/booting] Retrieval of the OS from secondary or tertiary store was thus eliminated as one of the characteristic operations for bootstrapping.
[src:barebox/booting] To allow system customizations, accessories, and other support software to be loaded automatically, the Atari's floppy drive was read for additional components during the boot process.
[src:barebox/booting] There was a timeout delay that provided time to manually insert a floppy as the system searched for the extra components.
[src:barebox/booting] This could be avoided by inserting a blank disk.
[src:barebox/booting] The IBM Personal Computer included ROM-based firmware called the BIOS; one of the functions of that firmware was to perform a power-on self test when the machine was powered up, and then to read software from a boot device and execute it.
[src:barebox/booting] Firmware compatible with the BIOS on the IBM Personal Computer is used in IBM PC compatible computers.
[src:barebox/booting] The UEFI was developed by Intel, originally for Itanium-based machines, and later also used as an alternative to the BIOS in x86-based machines, including Apple Macs using Intel processors.
[src:barebox/booting] Unix workstations originally had vendor-specific ROM-based firmware.
[src:barebox/booting] Sun Microsystems later developed OpenBoot, later known as Open Firmware, which incorporated a Forth interpreter, with much of the firmware being written in Forth.
[src:barebox/booting] It was standardized by the IEEE as IEEE standard 1275-1994; firmware that implements that standard was used in PowerPC-based Macs and some other PowerPC-based machines, as well as Sun's own SPARC-based computers.
[src:barebox/booting] The Advanced RISC Computing specification defined another firmware standard, which was implemented on some MIPS-based and Alpha-based machines and the SGI Visual Workstation x86-based workstations.
[src:barebox/booting] When a computer is turned off, its software‍—‌including operating systems, application code, and data‍—‌remains stored on non-volatile memory.
[src:barebox/booting] When the computer is powered on, it typically does not have an operating system or its loader in random-access memory (RAM).
[src:barebox/booting] The small program that starts this sequence is known as a *bootstrap loader*, *bootstrap* or *boot loader*.
[src:barebox/booting] Often, multiple-stage boot loaders are used, during which several programs of increasing complexity load one after the other in a process of chain loading.
[src:barebox/booting] Some earlier computer systems, upon receiving a boot signal from a human operator or a peripheral device, may load a very small number of fixed instructions into memory at a specific location, initialize at least one CPU, and then point the CPU to the instructions and start their execution.
[src:barebox/booting] These instructions typically start an input operation from some peripheral device (which may be switch-selectable by the operator).
[src:barebox/booting] Smaller computers often use less flexible but more automatic boot loader mechanisms to ensure that the computer starts quickly and with a predetermined software configuration.
[src:barebox/booting] In many desktop computers, for example, the bootstrapping process begins with the CPU executing software contained in ROM (for example, the BIOS of an IBM PC) at a predefined address (some CPUs, including the Intel x86 series are designed to execute this software after reset without outside help).
[src:barebox/booting] This software contains rudimentary functionality to search for devices eligible to participate in booting, and load a small program from a special section (most commonly the boot sector) of the most promising device, typically starting at a fixed entry point such as the start of the sector.
[src:barebox/booting] On systems with those constraints, the first program loaded into RAM may not be sufficiently large to load the operating system and, instead, must load another, larger program.
[src:barebox/booting] The first program loaded into RAM is called a first-stage boot loader, and the program it loads is called a second-stage boot loader.
[src:barebox/booting] On many embedded CPUs, the CPU built-in boot ROM, sometimes called the zero-stage boot loader, can find and load first-stage boot loaders.
[src:barebox/booting] Examples of first-stage (hardware initialization stage) boot loaders include BIOS, UEFI, coreboot, Libreboot and Das U-Boot.
[src:barebox/booting] On the IBM PC, the boot loader in the Master Boot Record (MBR) and the Partition Boot Record (PBR) was coded to require at least 32 KB (later expanded to 64 KB) of system memory and only use instructions supported by the original 8088/8086 processors.
[src:barebox/booting] The second-stage boot loader does not need drivers for its own operation, but may instead use generic storage access methods provided by system firmware such as the BIOS, UEFI or Open Firmware, though typically with restricted hardware functionality and lower performance.
[src:barebox/booting] Many boot loaders (like GNU GRUB, rEFInd, Windows's BOOTMGR, Syslinux, and Windows NT/2000/XP's NTLDR) can be configured to give the user multiple booting choices.
[src:barebox/booting] Some boot loaders can also load other boot loaders; for example, GRUB loads BOOTMGR instead of loading Windows directly.
[src:barebox/booting] Usually, a default choice is preselected with a time delay during which a user can press a key to change the choice; after this delay, the default choice is automatically run so normal booting can occur without interaction.
[src:barebox/booting] The boot process can be considered complete when the computer is ready to interact with the user, or the operating system is capable of running system programs or application programs.
[src:barebox/booting] Some boot loaders, such as Das U-Boot and iBoot, include both first- and second-stage boot functions.
[src:barebox/booting] Many embedded systems must boot immediately.
[src:barebox/booting] For example, waiting a minute for a digital television or a GPS navigation device to start is generally unacceptable.
[src:barebox/booting] Therefore, such devices have software systems in ROM or flash memory so the device can begin functioning immediately; little or no loading is necessary, because the loading can be precomputed and stored on the ROM when the device is made.
[src:barebox/booting] Large and complex systems may have boot procedures that proceed in multiple phases until finally the operating system and other programs are loaded and ready to execute.
[src:barebox/booting] Because operating systems are designed as if they never start or stop, a boot loader might load the operating system, configure itself as a mere process within that system, and then irrevocably transfer control to the operating system.
[src:barebox/booting] The boot loader then terminates normally as any other process would.
[src:barebox/booting] Most computers are also capable of booting over a computer network.
[src:barebox/booting] In this scenario, the operating system is stored on the disk of a server, and certain parts of it are transferred to the client using a simple protocol such as the Trivial File Transfer Protocol (TFTP).
[src:barebox/booting] After these parts have been transferred, the operating system takes over control of the booting process.
[src:barebox/booting] As with the second-stage boot loader, network booting begins by using generic network access methods provided by the network interface's boot ROM, which typically contains a Preboot Execution Environment (PXE) image.
[src:barebox/booting] No drivers are required, but the system functionality is limited until the operating system kernel and drivers are transferred and started.
[src:barebox/booting] As a result, once the ROM-based booting has completed it is entirely possible to network boot into an operating system that itself does not have the ability to use the network interface.
[src:barebox/booting] The boot device is the storage device from which the operating system is loaded.
[src:barebox/booting] Older, less common BIOS-bootable devices include floppy disk drives, Zip drives, and LS-120 drives.
[src:barebox/booting] IBM-compatible PCs are examples that use horizontal integrated hardware and UEFI/BIOS firmware.
[src:barebox/booting] Typically, the system firmware (UEFI or BIOS) will allow the user to configure a *boot order*.
[src:barebox/booting] If the boot order is set to "first, the DVD drive; second, the hard disk drive", then the firmware will try to boot from the DVD drive, and if this fails (e.g., because there is no DVD in the drive), it will try to boot from the local hard disk drive.
[src:barebox/booting] For example, on a PC with Windows installed on the hard drive, the user could set the boot order to the one given above, and then insert a Linux Live CD in order to try out Linux without having to install an operating system onto the hard drive.
[src:barebox/booting] This is an example of dual booting, in which the user chooses which operating system to start after the computer has performed its power-on self-test (POST).
[src:barebox/booting] Several devices are available that enable the user to *quick-boot* into what is usually a variant of Linux for various simple tasks such as Internet access; examples are Splashtop and Latitude ON.
[src:barebox/booting] This memory location typically contains a jump instruction that transfers execution to the location of the firmware (UEFI or BIOS) start-up program.
[src:barebox/booting] This program runs a power-on self-test (POST) to check and initialize required devices such as main memory (DRAM), the PCI bus and the PCI devices (including running embedded option ROMs).
[src:barebox/booting] One of the most involved steps is setting up DRAM over SPD, further complicated by the fact that, at this point, memory is very limited.
[src:barebox/booting] After initializing required hardware, the firmware (UEFI or BIOS) goes through a pre-configured list of non-volatile storage devices ("boot device sequence") until it finds one that is bootable.
[src:barebox/booting] Once the BIOS has found a bootable device it loads the boot sector to linear address 7C00h (usually segment:offset 0000h:7C00h, but some BIOSes erroneously use 07C0h:0000h) and transfers execution to the boot code.
[src:barebox/booting] In the case of a hard disk, this is referred to as the Master Boot Record (MBR).
[src:barebox/booting] The conventional MBR code checks the MBR's partition table for a partition set as *bootable* (the one with *active* flag set).
[src:barebox/booting] If an active partition is found, the MBR code loads the boot sector code from that partition, known as Volume Boot Record (VBR), and executes it.
[src:barebox/booting] The MBR boot code is often operating-system specific.
[src:barebox/booting] The boot sector code is the first-stage boot loader.
[src:barebox/booting] The boot loader was then able to load the first three sectors of the file into memory, which happened to contain another embedded boot loader able to load the remainder of the file into memory.
[src:barebox/booting] When Microsoft added LBA and FAT32 support, they even switched to a boot loader reaching over *two* physical sectors and using 386 instructions for size reasons.
[src:barebox/booting] At the same time, other vendors managed to squeeze much more functionality into a single boot sector without relaxing the original constraints on only minimal available memory (32 KB) and processor support (8088/8086).
[src:barebox/booting] For example, DR-DOS boot sectors are able to locate the boot file in the FAT12, FAT16 and FAT32 file system, and load it into memory as a whole via CHS or LBA, even if the file is not stored in a fixed location and in consecutive sectors.
[src:barebox/booting] The VBR is often OS-specific; however, its main function is to load and execute the operating system boot loader file (such as `bootmgr` or `ntldr`), which is the second-stage boot loader, from an active partition.
[src:barebox/booting] Then the boot loader loads the OS kernel from the storage device.
[src:barebox/booting] If there is no active partition, or the active partition's boot sector is invalid, the MBR may load a secondary boot loader which will select a partition (often via user input) and load its boot sector, which usually loads the corresponding operating system kernel.
[src:barebox/booting] In some cases, the MBR may also attempt to load secondary boot loaders before trying to boot the active partition.
[src:barebox/booting] If all else fails, it should issue an INT 18h BIOS interrupt call (followed by an INT 19h just in case INT 18h would return) in order to give back control to the BIOS, which would then attempt to boot off other devices, attempt a remote boot via network.
[src:barebox/booting] Many modern systems (Intel Macs and newer PCs) use UEFI.
[src:barebox/booting] Unlike BIOS, UEFI (not **Legacy boot** via CSM) does not rely on boot sectors, UEFI system loads the boot loader (**EFI application** file in USB disk or in the EFI System Partition) directly, and the OS kernel is loaded by the boot loader.
[src:barebox/booting] It is difficult to hardwire all the required logic for handling such devices, so an integrated boot ROM is used instead in such scenarios.
[src:barebox/booting] Also, a boot ROM may be able to load a boot loader or diagnostic program via serial interfaces like UART, SPI, USB and so on.
[src:barebox/booting] This feature is often used for system recovery purposes, or it could also be used for initial non-volatile memory programming when there is no software available in the non-volatile memory yet.
[src:barebox/booting] Many modern microcontrollers (e.g., flash memory controller on USB flash drives) have firmware ROM integrated directly into their silicon.
[src:barebox/booting] Some embedded system designs may also include an intermediary boot sequence step.
[src:barebox/booting] For example, Das U-Boot may be split into two stages: the platform would load a small SPL (Secondary Program Loader), which is a stripped-down version of U-Boot, and the SPL would do some initial hardware configuration (e.g.
[src:barebox/booting] DRAM initialization using CPU cache as RAM) and load the larger, fully featured version of U-Boot.
[src:barebox/booting] Such embedded systems may used highly customized and vertical integrated hardware and software, and their boot programs may be simpler.
[src:barebox/booting] Some CPUs and SoCs may not use CPU cache as RAM on boot process, they use an integrated boot processor to do some hardware configuration to reduce cost.
[src:barebox/booting] It is also possible to take control of a system by using a hardware debug interface such as JTAG.
[src:barebox/booting] Such an interface may be used to write the boot loader program into bootable non-volatile memory (e.g. flash) by instructing the processor core to perform the necessary actions to program non-volatile memory.
[src:barebox/booting] Alternatively, the debug interface may be used to upload some diagnostic or boot code into RAM, and then to start the processor core and instruct it to execute the uploaded code.
[src:barebox/booting] This allows, for example, the recovery of embedded systems where no software remains on any supported boot device, and where the processor does not have any integrated boot ROM.
[src:barebox/booting] JTAG is a standard and popular interface; many CPUs, microcontrollers and other devices are manufactured with JTAG interfaces (as of 2009).
[src:barebox/booting] Some microcontrollers provide special hardware interfaces that cannot be used to take arbitrary control of a system or directly run code, but instead allow the insertion of boot code into bootable non-volatile memory (like flash memory) via simple protocols.
[src:barebox/booting] Then, at the manufacturing phase, such interfaces are used to inject boot code (and possibly other code) into non-volatile memory.
[src:barebox/booting] After system reset, the microcontroller begins to execute code programmed into its non-volatile memory, just like usual processors use ROMs for booting.
[src:barebox/booting] Most notably, this technique is used by Atmel AVR microcontrollers, and by others as well.
[src:barebox/booting] In many cases, such interfaces are implemented by hardwired logic.
[src:barebox/booting] In other cases, such interfaces could be created by software running in integrated on-chip boot ROM from GPIO pins.
[src:barebox/booting] Most DSPs have a serial mode boot and a parallel mode boot, such as the host port interface (HPI boot).
[src:barebox/booting] In the case of DSPs, there is often a second microprocessor or microcontroller present in the system design, and this is responsible for overall system behavior, interrupt handling, dealing with external events, user interface, etc., while the DSP is dedicated to signal processing tasks only.
[src:barebox/booting] In such systems, the DSP could be booted by another processor, which is sometimes referred as the *host processor* (giving name to a Host Port).
[src:barebox/booting] Such a processor is also sometimes referred to as the *master*, since it usually boots first from its own memories and then controls overall system behavior, including booting of the DSP, and then further controls the DSP's behavior.
[src:barebox/booting] The DSP often lacks its own boot memories and relies on the host processor to supply the required code instead.
[src:barebox/booting] The most notable systems with such a design are cell phones, modems, audio and video players and so on, where a DSP and a CPU/microcontroller coexist.
[src:barebox/booting] Many FPGA chips load their configuration from an external configuration ROM, typically a serial EEPROM, on power-up.
[src:barebox/booting] Various measures have been implemented that enhance the security of the booting process.
[src:barebox/booting] Some of them are made mandatory, others can be disabled or enabled by the end user.
[src:barebox/booting] Traditionally, booting did not involve the use of cryptography.
[src:barebox/booting] The security can be bypassed by unlocking the boot loader, which might or might not be approved by the manufacturer.
[src:barebox/booting] Modern boot loaders make use of concurrency, meaning they can run multiple processor cores and threads at the same time, which adds extra layers of complexity to secure booting.
[src:barebox/booting] Matthew Garrett argued that booting security serves a legitimate goal, but in doing so chooses defaults that are hostile to users.
[src:barebox/booting] The system might exhibit its erroneous state in, for example, an explicit bootloop or a blue screen of death, before recovery is indicated.
[src:barebox/booting] Detection of an erroneous state may require a distributed event store and stream-processing platform for real-time operation of a distributed system.
[src:barebox/booting] An erroneous state can trigger bootloops; this state can be caused by misconfiguration from previously known-good operations.
[src:barebox/booting] Recovery attempts from that erroneous state then enter a reboot, in an attempt to return to a known-good state.
[src:barebox/booting] In Windows OS operations, for example, the recovery procedure was to reboot three times, the reboots needed to return to a usable menu.
[src:barebox/booting] Recovery might be specified via Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML), which can also implement Single sign-on (SSO) for some applications; in the zero trust security model, identification, authorization, and authentication are separable concerns in an SSO session.
[src:barebox/booting] When recovery of a site is indicated (viz., a blue screen of death is displayed on an airport terminal screen) personal site visits might be required to remediate the situation.
[src:barebox/bootloader] A **bootloader**, also spelled as **boot loader** or called **bootstrap loader**, is a computer program that is responsible for booting a computer and booting an operating system.
[src:barebox/bootloader] If it also provides an interactive menu with multiple boot choices then it is often called a **boot manager**.
[src:barebox/bootloader] Examples of first-stage bootloaders include BIOS, UEFI, coreboot, Libreboot, and Das U-Boot.
[src:barebox/bootloader] It initializes hardware devices such as CPU, motherboard, memory, storage and other I/O devices.
[src:barebox/bootloader] Second-stage boot loaders, such as GNU GRUB, rEFInd, BOOTMGR, Syslinux, and NTLDR, are not themselves operating systems, but are able to load an operating system properly and transfer execution to it; the operating system subsequently initializes itself and may load extra device drivers.
[src:barebox/bootloader] Second-stage implementations can include interactive user interfaces, allowing boot option selection and parameter modification.
[src:barebox/bootloader] They handle kernel loading, including processing of initrd/initramfs images, and can pass boot parameters to the kernel.
[src:barebox/bootloader] Many implement modular designs supporting loadable modules for additional functionality.
[src:barebox/bootloader] They may also handle compression, cryptographic verification, and chain-loading of other bootloaders.
[src:barebox/bootloader] In x86 computers, after the BIOS executes Power-On Self Test, it executes the first-stage bootloader, which is a compact 512-byte program that resides in the master boot record (MBR).
[src:barebox/bootloader] Running in 16-bit real mode at address 0x7C00, it locates the second-stage bootloader.
[src:barebox/bootloader] Its primary challenge lies in accomplishing these tasks within strict size constraints while handling potential hardware failures.
[src:barebox/bootloader] The bootloader must navigate disk structures, often implementing FAT file system support, and manage the delicate transition from the BIOS startup state to a stable environment for the next boot stage.
[src:barebox/bootloader] Microsoft boot sectors, therefore, traditionally imposed certain restrictions on the boot process.
[src:barebox/bootloader] For example, the boot file had to be located at a fixed position in the root directory of the file system and stored within consecutive sectors, conditions taken care of by the `SYS` command and slightly relaxed in later versions of DOS.
[src:barebox/bootloader] When Microsoft added logical block addressing (LBA) and FAT32 support, they switched to a boot loader reaching over *two* physical sectors, using 386 instructions for size reasons.
[src:barebox/bootloader] At the same time, other vendors managed to squeeze much more functionality into a single boot sector without relaxing the original constraints on only minimal available memory (32 KiB) and processor support (8088/8086).
[src:barebox/bootloader] For example, DR-DOS boot sectors are able to locate the boot file in the FAT12, FAT16 and FAT32 file systems, and load it into memory as a whole via CHS or LBA, even if the file is not stored in a fixed location and in consecutive sectors.
[src:barebox/bootloader] In x86 computers, second-stage bootloaders, such as PBR, operate without the strict 512-byte limitation of their first-stage counterparts.
[src:barebox/bootloader] They execute in a more sophisticated environment, typically ranging from 8KB to several megabytes in size.
[src:barebox/bootloader] This expanded space allows implementation of complex features such as filesystem support, runtime configuration, and bootloader menu interfaces.
[src:barebox/bootloader] The second-stage boot loader does not need drivers for its own operation, but may instead use generic storage access methods provided by system firmware such as the BIOS, though typically with restricted hardware functionality and lower performance.
[src:barebox/bootloader] In x86 computers, third-stage bootloaders include IO.SYS, NTLDR, BOOTMGR, and GRUB.
[src:barebox/bootloader] UEFI (except for CSM boot) does not rely on boot sectors; it directly loads the next-stage bootloader (such as BOOTMGR and GRUB2) from the EFI System Partition.
[src:barebox/bootloader] At the completion of the operation, the system stores the I/O address in the halfword at location 2 and loads the PSW from location 0.
[src:barebox/bootloader] The operating systems for S/360 through z/Architecture reside on direct access storage devices (DASDs), e.g., disk, drum.
[src:barebox/bootloader] For these devices, *Read IPL* does a seek to cylinder 000016, head 000016, and orients to record 0116.
[src:barebox/bootloader] For all supported operating systems, record 0116 contains a *Read Data* CCW to read a *bootstrap record* and a *Transfer In Channel* (TIC) CCW to the bootstrap.
[src:barebox/bootloader] The channel program in the bootstrap reads the IPL program text into location 0, beginning with a PSW pointing to the first IPL program text instruction.
[src:barebox/bootloader] For OS/360 the IPL program does some initialization, relocates itself, locates the *Nucleus*, loads the nucleus and transfers to the *Nucleus Initialization Program* (NIP) at the end of the Nucleus.
[src:barebox/bootloader] After these parts have been transferred, the operating system takes over the control of the booting process.
[src:barebox/das-u-boot] U-Boot is both a first-stage and second-stage bootloader.
[src:barebox/das-u-boot] It is loaded by the system's ROM (e.g. on-chip ROM of an ARM CPU) from a supported boot device, such as an SD card, SATA drive, NOR flash (e.g. using SPI or I²C), or NAND flash.
[src:barebox/das-u-boot] If there are size constraints, U-Boot may be split into two stages: the platform would load a small SPL (Secondary Program Loader), which is a stripped-down version of U-Boot, and the SPL would do some initial hardware configuration (e.g.
[src:barebox/das-u-boot] Regardless of whether the SPL is used, U-Boot performs both first-stage (e.g., configuring memory controller, SDRAM, mainboard and other I/O devices) and second-stage booting (e.g., loading OS kernel and other related files from storage device).
[src:barebox/das-u-boot] U-Boot implements a subset of the UEFI specification as defined in the Embedded Base Boot Requirements (EBBR) specification.
[src:barebox/das-u-boot] UEFI binaries like GRUB or the Linux kernel can be booted via the boot manager or from the command-line interface.
[src:barebox/das-u-boot] U-Boot runs a command-line interface on a console or a serial port.
[src:barebox/das-u-boot] Using the CLI, users can load and boot a kernel, possibly changing parameters from the default.
[src:barebox/das-u-boot] Because U-Boot's commands are fairly low-level, it takes several steps to boot a kernel, but this also makes U-Boot more flexible than other bootloaders, since the same commands can be used for more general tasks.
[src:barebox/das-u-boot] It's even possible to upgrade U-Boot using U-Boot, simply by reading the new bootloader from somewhere (local storage, or from the serial port or network) into memory, and writing that data to persistent storage where the bootloader belongs.
[src:barebox/das-u-boot] U-Boot has support for USB, so it can use a USB keyboard to operate the console (in addition to input from the serial port), and it can access and boot from USB Mass Storage devices such as SD card readers.
[src:barebox/das-u-boot] U-Boot boots an operating system by reading the kernel and any other required data (e.g. device tree, ramdisk image or boot image) into memory, and then executing the kernel with the appropriate arguments.
[src:barebox/das-u-boot] U-Boot's commands are actually generalized commands which can be used to read or write any arbitrary data.
[src:barebox/das-u-boot] (Note: These are boot sources from which U-Boot is capable of loading data (e.g. a kernel or ramdisk image) into memory.
[src:barebox/das-u-boot] On some embedded device implementations, the CPU or SoC will locate and load the bootloader (such as Das U-Boot) from the boot partition (such as ext4 or FAT filesystems) directly.
[src:barebox/das-u-boot] U-Boot does not need to be able to read a filesystem for the kernel to use it as a root filesystem or initial ramdisk; U-Boot simply provides an appropriate parameter to the kernel, and/or copies the data to memory without understanding its contents.
[src:barebox/das-u-boot] However, U-Boot can also read from (and in some cases, write to) filesystems.
[src:barebox/das-u-boot] This way, rather than requiring the data that U-Boot will load to be stored at a fixed location on the storage device, U-Boot can read the filesystem to search for and load the kernel, device tree, etc., by pathname.
[src:barebox/das-u-boot] The project started as a 8xx PowerPC bootloader called **8xxROM** written by Magnus Damm.
[src:barebox/das-u-boot] In October 1999 Wolfgang Denk moved the project to SourceForge.net and renamed it to **PPCBoot**, because SF.net did not allow project names starting with digits.
[src:barebox/das-u-boot] Version 0.4.1 of PPCBoot was first publicly released 19 July 2000.
[src:barebox/das-u-boot] In 2002 a previous version of the source code was briefly forked into a product called **ARMBoot**, but was merged back into the PPCBoot project shortly thereafter.
[src:barebox/das-u-boot] This marked the last release under the PPCBoot name, as it was renamed to reflect its ability to work on other architectures besides the PPC ISA.
[src:barebox/das-u-boot] PPCBoot−2.0.0 became **U−Boot−0.1.0** in November 2002, expanded to work on the x86 processor architecture.
[src:barebox/das-u-boot] Additional architecture capabilities were added in the following months: MIPS32 in March 2003, MIPS64 in April, Nios II in October, ColdFire in December, and MicroBlaze in April 2004.
[src:barebox/das-u-boot] The May 2004 release of U-Boot-1.1.2 worked on the products of 216 board manufacturers across the various architectures.
[src:barebox/das-u-boot] The current name **Das U-Boot** adds a German definite article, to create a bilingual pun on the classic 1981 German submarine film *Das Boot*, which takes place on a World War II German U-boat .
[src:barebox/das-u-boot] It is free software released under the terms of the GNU General Public License.
[src:barebox/das-u-boot] It can be built on an x86 PC for any of its intended architectures using a cross development GNU toolchain, for example crosstool, the Embedded Linux Development Kit (ELDK) or OSELAS.Toolchain.
[src:barebox/das-u-boot] In 2025, multiple vulnerabilities discovered in 2024 have been disclosed in U-Boot.
[src:barebox/das-u-boot] Abusing the filesystem support feature (ext4, SquashFS) of U-Boot by manually modifying filesystem data structures, an attacker can cause an integer overflow, a stack overflow or a heap overflow.
[src:barebox/das-u-boot] As a result, an attacker can perform an arbitrary code execution and bypass the boot chain of trust.
[src:barebox/das-u-boot] These issues are mitigated by the version v2025.01-rc1.
[src:barebox/device-tree] In computing, a **devicetree** (also written **device tree**) is a data structure describing the hardware components of a particular computer so that the operating system's kernel can use and manage those components, including the CPU or CPUs, the memory, the buses and the integrated peripherals.
[src:barebox/device-tree] The device tree was derived from SPARC-based and PowerPC-based computers via the Open Firmware project.
[src:barebox/device-tree] The current Devicetree specification is targeted at smaller systems and embedded systems, but is still used with some server-class systems (for instance, those described by the Power Architecture Platform Reference).
[src:barebox/device-tree] Personal computers with the x86 architecture generally do not use device trees, relying instead on various auto configuration protocols (e.g.
[src:barebox/device-tree] Systems which use device trees usually pass a static device tree (perhaps stored in EEPROM, or stored in NAND device like eUFS) to the operating system, but can also generate a device tree in the early stages of booting.
[src:barebox/device-tree] As an example, Das U-Boot and kexec can pass a device tree when launching a new operating system.
[src:barebox/device-tree] On systems with a boot loader that does not support device trees, a static device tree may be installed along with the operating system; the Linux kernel supports this approach.
[src:barebox/device-tree] The Devicetree specification is currently managed by a community named devicetree.org, which is associated with, among others, Linaro and Arm.
[src:barebox/device-tree] A device tree can hold any kind of data as internally it is a tree of named nodes and properties.
[src:barebox/device-tree] Nodes contain properties and child nodes, while properties are name–value pairs.
[src:barebox/device-tree] Device trees have both a binary format for operating systems to use and a textual format for convenient editing and management.
[src:barebox/device-tree] Given the correct device tree, the same compiled kernel can support different hardware configurations within a wider architecture family.
[src:barebox/device-tree] The Linux kernel for the ARC, ARM, C6x, H8/300, MicroBlaze, MIPS, NDS32, Nios II, OpenRISC, PowerPC, Power ISA, RISC-V, SuperH, and Xtensa architectures reads device tree information; on ARM, device trees have been mandatory for all new SoCs since 2012.
[src:barebox/device-tree] This can be seen as a remedy to the vast number of forks (of Linux and Das U-Boot) that have historically been created to support (marginally) different ARM boards.
[src:barebox/device-tree] The purpose is to move a significant part of the hardware description out of the kernel binary, and into the compiled device tree blob, which is handed to the kernel by the boot loader, replacing a range of board-specific C source files and compile-time options in the kernel.
[src:barebox/device-tree] It is specified in a Devicetree Source file (.dts) and is compiled into a Devicetree Blob or device tree binary (.dtb) file (also known as the flattened device tree) through the Devicetree compiler (DTC).
[src:barebox/device-tree] Device tree source files can include other files, referred to as device tree source includes.
[src:barebox/device-tree] It has been customary for ARM-based Linux distributions to include a boot loader that necessarily was customized for specific boards, for example Raspberry Pi or Hackberry A10.
[src:barebox/device-tree] This has created problems for the creators of Linux distributions as some part of the operating system must be compiled specifically for every board variant, or updated to support new boards.
[src:barebox/device-tree] However, some modern SoCs (for example, Freescale i.MX6) have a vendor-provided boot loader with device tree on a separate chip from the operating system.
[src:barebox/device-tree] A proprietary configuration file format used for similar purposes, the FEX file format, is a de facto standard among Allwinner SoCs.
[src:barebox/device-tree] Devicetree is widely used for ARM-based Android devices.
[src:barebox/device-tree] BSD can support device tree, as device tree usually adopted on embedded devices.
[src:barebox/device-tree] Windows does not use Devicetree (DTB file) as described here.
[src:barebox/device-tree] Instead, it uses ACPI to discover and manage devices.
[src:barebox/device-tree] On the boot process of iOS, iPadOS and ARM macOS, the Low-Level Bootloader (LLB) will load Apple-encrypted devicetree to main memory, then loads iBoot.
[src:barebox/device-tree] The coreboot project makes use of device trees, but they are different from the flattened device trees used in the Linux kernel.
[src:barebox/device-tree] In the example above, the line `/dts-v1/;` signifies version 1 of the DTS syntax.
[src:barebox/device-tree] The tree has four nodes: `/` (root node), `soc` (stands for "system on a chip"), `flash-controller@4001e000` and `flash@0` (instance of flash which uses the flash controller).
[src:barebox/device-tree] Besides these *node names*, the latter two nodes have *labels* `flash_controller` and `flash0` respectively.
[src:barebox/device-tree] The latter two nodes have *properties*, which represent name/value pairs.
[src:barebox/device-tree] Property `label` has string type, property `erase-block` has integer type and property `reg` is an array of integers (32-bit unsigned values).
[src:barebox/device-tree] Property values can refer to other nodes in the devicetree by their *phandles*.
[src:barebox/device-tree] Phandle for a node with label `flash0` would be written as `&flash0`.
[src:barebox/device-tree] Parts of the node names after the "at" sign (`@`) are *unit addresses*.
[src:barebox/device-tree] Unit addresses specify a node's resource address in the address space of its parent node.
[src:barebox/device-tree] The above tree could be compiled by the standard DTC compiler to binary DTB format or assembly.
[src:barebox/device-tree] In Zephyr RTOS, however, DTS files are compiled into C header files (.h), which are then used by the build system to compile code for a specific board.
[src:barebox/embedded-software] A precise and stable characteristic feature is that no or not all functions of embedded software are initiated/controlled via a human interface, but through machine-interfaces instead.
[src:barebox/embedded-software] Manufacturers build embedded software into the electronics of cars, telephones, modems, robots, appliances, toys, security systems, pacemakers, televisions and set-top boxes, and digital watches, for example.
[src:barebox/embedded-software] This software can be very simple, such as lighting controls running on an 8-bit microcontroller with a few kilobytes of memory with the suitable level of processing complexity determined with a Probably Approximately Correct Computation framework (a methodology based on randomized algorithms).
[src:barebox/embedded-software] However, embedded software can become very sophisticated in applications such as routers, optical network elements, airplanes, missiles, and process control systems.
[src:barebox/embedded-software] Unlike standard computers that generally use operating systems such as macOS, Windows or Linux, embedded software may use no operating system.
[src:barebox/embedded-software] When they do use one, a wide variety of operating systems can be chosen from, typically a real-time operating system.
[src:barebox/embedded-software] Code for embedded software is typically written in C or C++, but various high-level programming languages, such as C#, Java, Python and JavaScript, are now also in common use to target microcontrollers and embedded systems.
[src:barebox/embedded-software] Assembly languages are often used too, especially in booting and interrupt handling.
[src:barebox/embedded-software] Ada is used in some military and aviation projects.
[src:barebox/embedded-software] Most consumers are familiar with application software that provide functionality on a computer.
[src:barebox/embedded-software] However embedded software is often less visible, but no less complicated.
[src:barebox/embedded-software] Unlike application software, embedded software has fixed hardware requirements and capabilities, and addition of third-party hardware or software is strictly controlled.
[src:barebox/embedded-software] Embedded software needs to include all needed device drivers at manufacturing time, and the device drivers are written for the various hardware devices.
[src:barebox/embedded-software] The software is highly dependent on the CPU and specific chips chosen.
[src:barebox/embedded-software] Most embedded software engineers have at least a passing knowledge of reading schematics, and reading data sheets for components to determine usage of registers and communication system.
[src:barebox/embedded-software] Conversion between decimal, hexadecimal and binary is useful as well as using bit manipulation.
[src:barebox/embedded-software] Web applications are often used for managing hardware, although XML files and other output may be passed to a computer for display.
[src:barebox/embedded-software] File systems with folders are typically used, however SQL databases are often absent.
[src:barebox/embedded-software] Software development requires use of a cross compiler, which runs on a computer but produces executable code for the target device.
[src:barebox/embedded-software] Debugging requires use of an in-circuit emulator, and debugging hardware such as JTAG or SWD debuggers.
[src:barebox/embedded-software] Software developers often have access to the complete kernel (OS) source code.
[src:barebox/embedded-software] Size of the storage memory and RAM can vary significantly.
[src:barebox/embedded-software] Some systems run in 16 KB of Flash and 4 KB of RAM with a CPU operating at 8 MHz, other systems can rival contemporary computers.
[src:barebox/embedded-software] These space requirements lead to more work being done in C or embedded C++, instead of C++.
[src:barebox/embedded-software] Interpreted languages like BASIC (while e.g.
[src:barebox/embedded-software] Parallax Propeller can use compiled BASIC) and Java (Java ME Embedded 8.3 is available for e.g.
[src:barebox/embedded-software] ARM Cortex-M4, Cortex-M7 microcontrollers and older ARM11 used in Raspberry Pi and Intel Galileo Gen.
[src:barebox/embedded-software] 2) are not commonly used; while an implementation of the interpreted Python 3 language – MicroPython – is however available expressly for microcontroller use, e.g.
[src:barebox/embedded-software] 32-bit ARM-based (such as BBC micro:bit) and 16-bit PIC microcontrollers.
[src:barebox/embedded-software] Communications between processors and between one processor and other components are essential.
[src:barebox/embedded-software] Besides direct memory addressing, hardware level common protocols include I²C, SPI, serial ports, 1-Wires, Ethernets, and USB.
[src:barebox/embedded-software] Communications protocols designed for use in embedded systems are available as closed source from companies including InterNiche Technologies and CMX Systems.
[src:barebox/embedded-software] Open-source protocols stem from uIP, lwip, and others.
